Headlines.Author: Erin McCarthy
Headlines.Headline: TECO Energy to Sell Coal Mining Business for $170 Million

PARAGRAPH.#text: TECO Energy Inc. said Monday it is exiting the coal mining business completely with the planned sale of its coal mining subsidiary TECO Coal. The energy-related holding company said Monday it has agreed to sell TECO Coal and its subsidiaries to Cambrian Coal Corporation for $170 million. The move comes amid a prolonged market slump in coal, which has led to cost-cutting and the closing of some coal mines from other mining companies this year. "This transaction will result in a complete exit from the coal mining business," TECO Energy Chief Executive Officer John Ramil said in a statement.

Headlines.Headline: Army Corps Suspends Permit Program For Surface Coal Mines

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Updates with comment from environmental and industry groups, additional background.) The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers has suspended a fast-track permitting process for surface coal mines in the Appalachia region amid growing concerns over their environmental impact. The suspension, announced Thursday, comes as federal regulators take steps to tighten oversight of mining in the region, particularly to limit so-called mountaintop-removal mining. The process, primarily used in Kentucky and West Virginia, involves blasting the tops off mountains to access the coal beneath.

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Teco Energy Inc.

Monday said it agreed to sell its Teco Transport Corp. unit to an investment group led by an affiliate of private-equity firm Greenstreet Equity Partners for $405 million in cash. The Tampa-based energy company estimates net proceeds of about $370 million to $380 million, and said it expects the deal to close before year-end. Shares of Teco closed Friday at $16.74.

Headlines.Author: Sam Favate
Headlines.Headline: Tampa Electric Defers Use Of Clean Coal Tech Beyond 2013

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Tampa Electric Co., a unit of Teco Energy Inc.

, Thursday said it no longer plans to meet its 2013 need for baseload generation through the use of "clean coal," or integrated gasification combined-cycle technology. The company said the decision was due to "continued uncertainty related to carbon dioxide regulations," and "the economic risk of these factors to customers and investors." President Chuck Black said in a statement, "We believe there is a role for IGCC in Tampa Electric's future generation plans, but with the uncertainty of carbon capture and sequestration regulations being discussed at the federal and state levels, the timing is not right to utilize it for a baseload facility needed by 2013.

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Teco Energy

on Thursday said second-quarter net income rose 18% to $73.7 million, or 35 cents a share from $62.5 million, or 30 cents a share in the year-ago period. Headlines.Author: Melissa Korn
Headlines.Headline: Teco Energy Files With State For Coal Gasification Plant

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Teco Energy Inc.

filed a petition with the Florida Public Service Commission to build a 632-megawatt Polk Unit 6, an integrated coal gasification combined cycle facility in Polk County, Fla. The Tampa-based energy holding company said the project, which would deal with carbon emissions among fossil fuel technologies, would cost about $2 billion. Teco received $133.5 million in clean coal tax credits from the Internal Revenue Service and Department of Energy in November for Polk 6 and is now  waiting for regulatory approval before beginning to build the plant.

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Altera beats expectations 7-15-98

#text: Chipmaker Altera Corp. (ALTR)

may get a boost Thursday following a profit report that exceeded analysts' expectations.
    Altera earned operating income of 40 cents a share, surpassing the average estimate of
    analysts surveyed by First Call by 2 cents. Shares ended the session up 2 5/8 at 36 3/4.
